<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Federal Findings Digest — January 2026 — The Language Firm</title>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Fraunces:ital,opsz,wght@0,9..144,300;0,9..144,600;0,9..144,700;1,9..144,400&family=DM+Sans:wght@400;500;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
  :root {
    --dark:     #1B3A4B;
    --accent:   #1A5FA0;
    --amber:    #A85D1A;
    --green:    #2E5E4A;
    --green-bg: #D4EDE4;
    --amber-bg: #F5E0C8;
    --blue-bg:  #D4E6F5;
    --red:      #8B1A2A;
    --red-bg:   #F0D4D8;
    --purple:   #4A2E7A;
    --purple-bg:#EDE4F5;
    --gray:     #6B7C8A;
    --gray-lt:  #E8EDF1;
    --body:     #333333;
    --bg:       #F2F4F6;
    --white:    #FFFFFF;
  }
  * { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }
  body { background: var(--bg); font-family: 'DM Sans', sans-serif; color: var(--body); line-height: 1.6; }
  .cal-wrap { max-width: 960px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 48px 24px 64px; }
 
  .cal-header { margin-bottom: 28px; animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease both 0.05s; }
  .cal-eyebrow { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 3px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 10px; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .cal-eyebrow::before { content: ''; display: inline-block; width: 22px; height: 2px; background: var(--accent); }
  .cal-title { font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-size: clamp(28px, 4vw, 42px); font-weight: 700; color: var(--dark); line-height: 1.15; margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .cal-title em { font-style: italic; font-weight: 300; color: var(--accent); }
  .cal-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .cal-desc { font-size: 14.5px; color: var(--gray); max-width: 680px; line-height: 1.7; }
 
  /* TRANSITION ALERT — top of page, high visibility */
  .transition-alert {
    background: var(--dark);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 24px 28px;
    margin-bottom: 28px;
    animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease both 0.08s;
  }
  .transition-alert-label {
    font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 3px; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .transition-alert-title {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--white); line-height: 1.2; margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .transition-alert-body {
    font-size: 13.5px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.75); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .transition-alert-body strong { color: var(--white); }
  .source-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); padding-top: 14px; }
  .source-list li { font-size: 12px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); padding-left: 16px; position: relative; line-height: 1.5; }
  .source-list li::before { content: '→'; position: absolute; left: 0; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.3); font-size: 10px; top: 2px; }
  .source-list li a { color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6); text-decoration: none; }
  .source-list li a:hover { color: var(--white); }
 
  .cal-context { background: var(--white); border-left: 4px solid var(--purple); border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0; padding: 18px 20px; margin-bottom: 28px; font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--gray); line-height: 1.65; animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease both 0.1s; }
  .cal-context strong { color: var(--dark); }
 
  .cal-filters { display: flex; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 36px; animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease both 0.15s; }
  .f-pill { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 1px; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 8px 18px; border-radius: 3px; border: 2px solid var(--gray-lt); cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.2s; background: var(--white); color: var(--gray); }
  .f-pill.active { background: var(--dark); color: var(--white); border-color: var(--dark); }
  .f-pill:hover:not(.active) { border-color: var(--accent); color: var(--accent); }
 
  .cal-section-label { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 3px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--gray); padding: 6px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--gray-lt); margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 8px; }
 
  .cal-entries { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 16px; }
  .cal-entry { background: var(--white); border-radius: 6px; overflow: hidden; box-shadow: 0 1px 6px rgba(27,58,75,0.07); transition: box-shadow 0.2s, transform 0.2s; animation: fadeUp 0.4s ease both; }
  .cal-entry:hover { box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(27,58,75,0.12); transform: translateY(-1px); }
  .cal-entry.title1 { border-left: 5px solid var(--accent); }
  .cal-entry.ocr    { border-left: 5px solid var(--purple); }
  .cal-entry.hidden { display: none; }
 
  .entry-inner { padding: 22px 26px; }
  .entry-top { display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 14px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .entry-badge { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 1.5px; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 4px 10px; border-radius: 2px; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 2px; }
  .title1 .entry-badge { background: var(--blue-bg); color: var(--accent); }
  .ocr    .entry-badge { background: var(--purple-bg); color: var(--purple); }
  .entry-type-badge { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 1.5px; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 4px 10px; border-radius: 2px; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 2px; }
  .entry-type-badge.dcl  { background: var(--blue-bg);   color: var(--accent); }
  .entry-type-badge.invest { background: var(--purple-bg); color: var(--purple); }
 
  .entry-title-block { flex: 1; min-width: 200px; }
  .entry-title { font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-size: 17px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--dark); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 3px; }
  .entry-date  { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.3px; color: var(--gray); }
 
  .entry-sublabel { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 2px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--dark); margin-bottom: 6px; margin-top: 14px; }
  .entry-body { font-size: 13.5px; line-height: 1.65; color: #555; margin-bottom: 14px; }
 
  .entry-tlf-note { font-size: 13px; color: var(--dark); background: var(--blue-bg); border-radius: 3px; padding: 12px 16px; margin-bottom: 14px; line-height: 1.6; border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); }
  .ocr .entry-tlf-note { background: var(--purple-bg); border-left-color: var(--purple); }
 
  .entry-action { background: var(--green-bg); border-left: 4px solid var(--green); border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0; padding: 14px 16px; margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .entry-action-label { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 2px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--green); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .entry-action ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .entry-action ul li { font-size: 13px; color: #1A3A2A; padding-left: 18px; position: relative; line-height: 1.55; }
  .entry-action ul li::before { content: '→'; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--green); font-size: 11px; top: 2px; }
 
  .entry-source { font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--gray); line-height: 1.5; margin-top: 10px; }
  .entry-source strong { color: var(--dark); font-weight: 700; }
  .entry-source a { color: var(--accent); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; }
  .entry-source a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
 
  .cal-statbar { display: flex; background: var(--dark); border-radius: 6px; overflow: hidden; margin-top: 40px; animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease both 0.3s; }
  .cal-stat { flex: 1; padding: 22px 28px; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); }
  .cal-stat:last-child { border-right: none; }
  .cal-stat-val { font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--white); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .cal-stat-lbl { font-size: 12px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); line-height: 1.4; }
 
  .cal-footer-note { margin-top: 32px; padding: 20px 24px; background: var(--white); border-radius: 6px; border-left: 4px solid var(--amber); font-size: 13px; color: var(--gray); line-height: 1.65; animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease both 0.35s; }
  .cal-footer-note strong { color: var(--dark); }
 
  @keyframes fadeUp { from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(12px); } to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); } }
 
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .cal-wrap { padding: 32px 16px 48px; }
    .cal-statbar { flex-direction: column; }
    .cal-stat { border-right: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); }
    .cal-stat:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="cal-wrap">
 
  <div class="cal-header">
    <div class="cal-eyebrow">The Language Firm — Federal Integrity Track</div>
    <h1 class="cal-title">Federal Findings<br><em>Digest</em></h1>
    <p class="cal-meta">January 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong>2 findings</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; Published March 16, 2026</p>
    <p class="cal-desc">Federal programs &amp; fiscal compliance intelligence for K-12 federal program directors, fiscal agents, and district administrators.</p>
  </div>
 
  <!-- TRANSITION ALERT — first thing the reader sees -->
  <div class="transition-alert">
    <div class="transition-alert-label">Why this issue is short — documented</div>
    <div class="transition-alert-title">January 2026 had low federal output due to the administration transition.</div>
    <div class="transition-alert-body">
      January 20, 2026 was Inauguration Day. The first full month of a new administration is structurally low in program guidance output — incoming leadership had not yet been confirmed, the Department of Education was operating under a continuing resolution that restricted major agency actions, and normal guidance channels were effectively paused while the new administration established its policy priorities through executive orders rather than program guidance.
      <br><br>
      <strong>This is documented and expected, not an editorial gap.</strong> The two findings included in this issue — one Dear Colleague Letter issued on January 21 (the day after inauguration) and one OCR directed investigation announced in early March with a January trigger — represent the material K-12 compliance activity that was actually published. Months with administration transitions, continuing resolutions, or significant regulatory freezes produce fewer actionable program documents. The digest reports what exists, not what a typical month might produce. February 2026 returned to normal output volume.
    </div>
    <ul class="source-list">
      <li>Department of Education operating under continuing resolution through January 30, 2026, restricting reduction-in-force notices and major agency actions. <a href="https://www.nasfaa.org/news-item/37687/White_House_Continues_Effort_to_Dismantle_ED_With_New_Agency_Partnerships" target="_blank">NASFAA documentation ↗</a></li>
      <li>Trump administration inaugurated January 20, 2026. Several executive orders affecting K-12 education signed in the days immediately following inauguration, including orders on DEI, Title IX enforcement posture, and school choice, shifting agency focus from program guidance to executive order implementation.</li>
      <li>FY 2026 full-year appropriations not passed until February 3, 2026, leaving the Department without confirmed budget authority for the entirety of January. <a href="https://education.vermont.gov/news/federal-updates" target="_blank">Vermont Agency of Education federal tracking ↗</a></li>
      <li>Linda McMahon not confirmed as Secretary of Education until after the transition period, leaving the Department under acting leadership during the January guidance window.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-context">
    <strong>How this digest works.</strong> Each entry summarizes a federal finding, enforcement action, resolution agreement, guidance document, or regulatory activity published in January 2026. Every entry includes a factual summary of the source document, a TLF interpretation of the compliance implication, and a Your Action section translating that implication into concrete steps. Source links are provided for independent verification.
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-filters">
    <div class="f-pill active" data-filter="all" onclick="filterProgram('all')">All programs</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="title1" onclick="filterProgram('title1')">Title I</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="ocr" onclick="filterProgram('ocr')">OCR / Title IX</div>
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-entries" id="entries">
 
    <!-- TITLE I -->
    <div class="cal-section-label" data-section="title1">Title I</div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry title1" data-program="title1">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">Title I</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge dcl">Dear Colleague Letter</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">Department of Education Encourages States to Maximize Title I Schoolwide Program Flexibilities</div>
            <div class="entry-date">U.S. Department of Education, Office of Elementary and Secondary Education · January 21, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
 
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">The Department sent a letter to all chief state school officers encouraging states to approve any Title I school to implement a schoolwide program and consolidate federal, state, and local funds to reduce red tape and compliance costs. While 86% of Title I schools operate schoolwide programs, very few consolidate funds. States are urged to expand schoolwide eligibility and support districts in using this flexibility.</p>
 
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">
          This Dear Colleague Letter directs state education agencies to maximize Title I schoolwide program flexibilities by approving any Title I school to operate schoolwide and consolidate federal, state, and local funds, regardless of the traditional 40% poverty threshold. For federal programs directors, this signals an administrative push to reduce compliance burden through fund consolidation, though the letter itself does not change statutory requirements under ESEA Section 1114. The letter was issued the day after inauguration and reflects the new administration's early posture on reducing federal compliance overhead in Title I administration. Districts operating Title I schoolwide programs should review current fund consolidation practices and consult with their state Title I office on any expanded eligibility guidance issued in response to this letter.
        </div>
 
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Contact your state Title I office to ask whether the state intends to issue guidance on expanded schoolwide eligibility in response to this Dear Colleague Letter. Any change in state eligibility thresholds affects your school's options.</li>
            <li>Review your current Title I schoolwide plan to confirm strategic activities are documented in your comprehensive needs assessment. If you are not currently operating schoolwide, determine whether your school now qualifies under expanded state criteria.</li>
            <li>If considering fund consolidation, verify supplement-not-supplant documentation is in place. Consolidation does not eliminate fiscal accountability requirements — it changes how they are documented.</li>
            <li>Note that this letter signals direction, not a statutory change. Do not adjust budgets or plans based on this letter alone. Wait for state guidance before making consolidation decisions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
 
        <div class="entry-source">
          <strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-education-encourages-states-maximize-schoolwide-program-flexibilities-improve-student-success" target="_blank">U.S. Department of Education press release, January 21, 2026 ↗</a> · ESEA Section 1114 (schoolwide programs) · 34 CFR §200.25 (fund consolidation)
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- OCR / TITLE IX -->
    <div class="cal-section-label" data-section="ocr">OCR / Title IX</div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry ocr" data-program="ocr">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">OCR / Title IX</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge invest">Directed Investigation</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">OCR Initiates Title IX Investigation into New Richmond School District (Wisconsin) Over Bathroom Policy</div>
            <div class="entry-date">U.S. Department of Education, Office for Civil Rights · Announced March 5, 2026 · Triggered by January 2026 events</div>
          </div>
        </div>
 
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">OCR initiated a directed investigation into New Richmond School District based on reports the district allows students to access intimate facilities based on gender identity rather than biological sex. Parents raised concerns at a January 2026 board meeting. OCR will determine whether the district violated Title IX. This represents the Trump administration's enforcement approach under 2020 Title IX regulations.</p>
 
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">
          This directed investigation signals the current administration's Title IX enforcement posture on facility access. OCR used a January 2026 parent complaint as the basis for a directed investigation, meaning OCR initiated the review itself rather than waiting for a formal complaint to proceed through standard channels. This puts all districts on notice that policies allowing students to use facilities aligned with gender identity rather than sex assigned at birth are now an active OCR enforcement priority. The investigation does not produce a finding — it opens a compliance review. Districts should document the legal basis for current facility access policies and ensure coordination between their Title IX coordinator, legal counsel, and board governance before any policy amendment.
        </div>
 
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Review your board-approved policy governing locker rooms, restrooms, and other sex-separated facilities. Confirm the policy reflects a deliberate, documented legal interpretation — not an informal practice.</li>
            <li>Brief your Title IX coordinator and legal counsel on this investigation. The enforcement signal is clear: OCR is actively reviewing facility access policies under the 2020 Title IX regulations. Your coordinator needs to understand the current federal posture.</li>
            <li>Document the legal basis for your current practice, whatever it is. A policy that has been reviewed, discussed with counsel, and approved by the board is defensible. An undocumented informal practice is not.</li>
            <li>Do not make policy changes solely in response to this investigation without consulting legal counsel. State law may govern this question independently of the federal posture, and changes made under pressure without legal review create their own exposure.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
 
        <div class="entry-source">
          <strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-education-initiates-title-ix-investigation-wisconsin-school-district-over-alleged-use-of-womens-restrooms-biological-men" target="_blank">U.S. Department of Education press release, March 5, 2026 ↗</a> · 2020 Title IX regulations (34 CFR Part 106) · Originated from January 2026 parent complaint at New Richmond School District board meeting
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-statbar">
    <div class="cal-stat">
      <div class="cal-stat-val">2 findings</div>
      <div class="cal-stat-lbl">Material K-12 federal documents published or triggered in January 2026</div>
    </div>
    <div class="cal-stat">
      <div class="cal-stat-val">Transition month</div>
      <div class="cal-stat-lbl">Low output documented — new administration, continuing resolution, no confirmed Secretary</div>
    </div>
    <div class="cal-stat">
      <div class="cal-stat-val">Your Action</div>
      <div class="cal-stat-lbl">Both entries include concrete steps for your team</div>
    </div>
    <div class="cal-stat">
      <div class="cal-stat-val">Source-cited</div>
      <div class="cal-stat-lbl">Every finding links to the primary federal document</div>
    </div>
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-footer-note">
    <strong>About this issue's accuracy standards.</strong> Every entry cites a primary source document. The low-output explanation for January 2026 cites documented federal actions including the continuing resolution, inauguration date, and appropriations timeline. TLF interpretations reflect the compliance implication for K-12 federal programs as of the publication date. Your Action items are practice guidance and do not represent regulatory requirements unless explicitly noted. This digest does not constitute legal advice. Verify all findings against original source documents before taking compliance action.
    <br><br>
    The Language Firm · languagefirm.org · Federal Integrity Track · January 2026
  </div>
 
</div>
 
<script>
  function filterProgram(filter) {
    document.querySelectorAll('.f-pill').forEach(p => p.classList.toggle('active', p.dataset.filter === filter));
    let delay = 0;
    document.querySelectorAll('.cal-entry').forEach(entry => {
      const show = filter === 'all' || entry.dataset.program === filter;
      entry.classList.toggle('hidden', !show);
      if (show) {
        entry.style.animationDelay = (delay * 0.06) + 's';
        entry.style.animation = 'none';
        void entry.offsetHeight;
        entry.style.animation = '';
        delay++;
      }
    });
    document.querySelectorAll('.cal-section-label').forEach(label => {
      const section = label.dataset.section;
      label.style.display = (filter === 'all' || section === filter) ? '' : 'none';
    });
  }
</script>
</body>
</html>
 
